00:01:23.020 --> 00:01:24.250
ROMAIN TROUBLE: Hi, everyone.

00:01:24.250 --> 00:01:24.970
I'm Romain.

00:01:24.970 --> 00:01:26.020
I'm a sailor.

00:01:26.020 --> 00:01:30.280
I sailed America's cup twice
in my life when I was younger.

00:01:30.280 --> 00:01:34.010
And I also studied biology
when I was younger.

00:01:34.010 --> 00:01:35.550
Now, I am old and 40 years old.

00:01:35.550 --> 00:01:38.800
But I'm heading
Tara since 15 years

00:01:38.800 --> 00:01:43.960
now as Etienne Bourgois, the
President of the foundation.

00:01:43.960 --> 00:01:45.250
We study the ocean.

00:01:45.250 --> 00:01:45.970
I'm a sailor.

00:01:45.970 --> 00:01:46.810
We are sailors.

00:01:46.810 --> 00:01:50.770
We're also scientists,
as [? Johan ?] told you.

00:01:50.770 --> 00:01:53.320
We are all together on
the spaceship Earth,

00:01:53.320 --> 00:01:56.740
across the universe, at
millions of kilometers an hour.

00:01:56.740 --> 00:02:03.240
And we barely know a few
things about this planet.

00:02:03.240 --> 00:02:04.572
She's blue.

00:02:04.572 --> 00:02:07.030
When you ask all the astronauts,
and I asked Thomas Pesquet

00:02:07.030 --> 00:02:09.329
recently, how's the
planet from the sky?

00:02:09.329 --> 00:02:10.120
He said, it's blue.

00:02:10.120 --> 00:02:11.100
It's a blue planet.

00:02:11.100 --> 00:02:16.110
And 70% of the planet
is made of ocean--

00:02:16.110 --> 00:02:20.740
huge, it will change with the
atmosphere, a huge playground

00:02:20.740 --> 00:02:23.500
for sailors, of course.

00:02:23.500 --> 00:02:26.770
But if you take off all
the water of the planet,

00:02:26.770 --> 00:02:29.430
and you want to put
it in a sphere--

00:02:29.430 --> 00:02:32.000
just to give you an
idea of the volume--

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:35.260
this is the air we breathe.

00:02:35.260 --> 00:02:36.990
The atmosphere we
put in the sphere,

00:02:36.990 --> 00:02:38.830
the sphere is this size.

00:02:38.830 --> 00:02:42.260
And if you do the same with
all the water of the planet,

00:02:42.260 --> 00:02:44.290
this is the ocean water--

00:02:44.290 --> 00:02:49.170
very, very tiny ball of
1,400 kilometers in diameter.

00:02:49.170 --> 00:02:52.630
The tiny dots here
is the fresh water,

00:02:52.630 --> 00:02:55.580
and the smaller dots
is drinkable water.

00:02:55.580 --> 00:03:00.310
And our life depends on
this small ball of ocean.

00:03:00.310 --> 00:03:04.630
When you breathe, when you
get proteins from the ocean,

00:03:04.630 --> 00:03:07.540
the CO2 is stored in
this ocean mainly.

00:03:07.540 --> 00:03:11.340
So this is really your
life support system.

00:03:11.340 --> 00:03:16.120
So on Tara, we try to take you
on a trip, take the planet,

00:03:16.120 --> 00:03:19.950
take humanity on a trip on
science, discover the planet,

00:03:19.950 --> 00:03:24.010
try to understand its
fates, where we go on this.

00:03:24.010 --> 00:03:27.340
We try to share that with
as many people as we can

00:03:27.340 --> 00:03:29.110
through the media,
through the Google,

00:03:29.110 --> 00:03:31.780
through YouTube,
through the networks.

00:03:31.780 --> 00:03:33.250
In many places we
go in the world,

00:03:33.250 --> 00:03:38.650
we've been visiting about 65
countries over the last 10

00:03:38.650 --> 00:03:42.370
years, which is a big trip.

00:03:42.370 --> 00:03:46.060
Of course, we share that
with kids in the schools,

00:03:46.060 --> 00:03:47.660
mainly French-speaking
schools today,

00:03:47.660 --> 00:03:52.345
but we are now developing
curricula for overseas.

00:03:55.750 --> 00:03:57.390
We also teach the
southern countries

00:03:57.390 --> 00:04:00.820
how to go in the ocean, how
to set up scientific boats,

00:04:00.820 --> 00:04:06.040
how to understand, how to
use the richness of the ocean

00:04:06.040 --> 00:04:10.420
for their behavior, for their
economy, for their development.

00:04:10.420 --> 00:04:13.270
And this is a very
strong commitment

00:04:13.270 --> 00:04:15.730
we've got since two years now.

00:04:15.730 --> 00:04:17.320
And also, as
[? Johan ?] told you,

00:04:17.320 --> 00:04:22.370
we are putting some scientists
on ocean at the UN every three,

00:04:22.370 --> 00:04:26.530
four months to teach as well.

00:04:26.530 --> 00:04:29.950
The people, the kids,
the southern countries,

00:04:29.950 --> 00:04:33.050
and the states, and
the negotiators.

00:04:33.050 --> 00:04:37.330
So over the last 15 years--

00:04:37.330 --> 00:04:39.840
soon 15 years-- we
did many projects.

00:04:39.840 --> 00:04:41.020
But we'll meet four of them.

00:04:41.020 --> 00:04:42.977
And I will try to explain
to you what we did

00:04:42.977 --> 00:04:43.810
and why we did that.

00:04:43.810 --> 00:04:48.460
We did one 10 years ago on
the climate in the Arctic.

00:04:48.460 --> 00:04:51.670
We did another one four
years in a row fishing

00:04:51.670 --> 00:04:54.910
plankton, invisible animals.

00:04:54.910 --> 00:04:55.660
You fish.

00:04:55.660 --> 00:04:56.826
You don't see what you fish.

00:04:56.826 --> 00:04:58.720
But you fish every
day for four years--

00:04:58.720 --> 00:04:59.800
crazy, crazy, you think.

00:04:59.800 --> 00:05:02.470
You're really crazy guys.

00:05:02.470 --> 00:05:05.290
Of course, when you fish
plankton across the ocean,

00:05:05.290 --> 00:05:06.710
you fish a lot of plastic.

00:05:06.710 --> 00:05:10.720
And this is one of the main
disasters we're facing today.

00:05:10.720 --> 00:05:12.190
This is a reversible disaster.

00:05:12.190 --> 00:05:13.960
If we do something,
we will stop that.

00:05:13.960 --> 00:05:16.420
But this is a very
important disaster.

00:05:16.420 --> 00:05:19.870
And we also spent
a lot of time--

00:05:19.870 --> 00:05:21.370
right now, the boat
is at the middle

00:05:21.370 --> 00:05:24.130
of this two-year
expedition in the Pacific.

00:05:24.130 --> 00:05:28.540
She was this morning in Kimbe
Bay in Papua, New Guinea,

00:05:28.540 --> 00:05:31.400
getting ready for a new survey
in this part of the island.

00:05:31.400 --> 00:05:33.690
We study the coral
reef ecosystem

00:05:33.690 --> 00:05:36.570
over all the Pacific for
two and a half years.

00:05:36.570 --> 00:05:38.830
This is now.

00:05:38.830 --> 00:05:41.560
Back, 10 years ago, we
studied the Arctic Ocean.

00:05:41.560 --> 00:05:43.330
This is North Pole.

00:05:43.330 --> 00:05:45.920
This is the Arctic region.

00:05:45.920 --> 00:05:47.620
And you can see the
North Pole here.

00:05:47.620 --> 00:05:52.090
And this was done
by a guy, crazy guy,

00:05:52.090 --> 00:05:54.260
who wanted to be the first
guy at the North Pole

00:05:54.260 --> 00:05:57.160
a century before called Nansen.

00:05:57.160 --> 00:06:00.680
He missed his goal, but we did
the same track, the only one

00:06:00.680 --> 00:06:02.730
to do it, 10 years ago.

00:06:02.730 --> 00:06:06.611
And we drifted across the
Arctic Ocean doing science--

00:06:06.611 --> 00:06:08.860
now, we'll not go into
details-- but took measurements

00:06:08.860 --> 00:06:13.310
everywhere, down in the water,
in the atmosphere, on the ice.

00:06:13.310 --> 00:06:16.240
We did six months of dark--
in the dark six months.

00:06:16.240 --> 00:06:19.120
This expedition lasted
a year and a half.

00:06:19.120 --> 00:06:24.230
Six months in the dark,
nonstop, pushed by the winds,

00:06:24.230 --> 00:06:26.090
the ice is crossing
the ocean-- we did

00:06:26.090 --> 00:06:29.150
5,000 kilometers doing nothing.

00:06:29.150 --> 00:06:32.090
The world of Tara, this
world that you see here,

00:06:32.090 --> 00:06:34.570
is drifting 10 kilometers
per day in the Arctic,

00:06:34.570 --> 00:06:37.670
pushed by the prevailing winds.

00:06:37.670 --> 00:06:41.960
And if you look at how it works,
it's like tectonic plates.

00:06:41.960 --> 00:06:46.770
We can have the sound
here maybe in the--

00:06:46.770 --> 00:06:50.270
put up the volume, please.

00:06:50.270 --> 00:06:52.850
And the plates in the Arctic,
they move not the same speed.

00:06:52.850 --> 00:06:55.370
And sometimes, they
crush the boat.

00:06:55.370 --> 00:06:56.720
This is real time.

00:06:56.720 --> 00:07:01.340
And nothing we do in our
planet can stop that.

00:07:01.340 --> 00:07:04.389
The energy of the
Arctic is colossal.

00:07:04.389 --> 00:07:05.826
[CLICKING SOUNDS]

00:07:10.620 --> 00:07:14.190
This world is drifting
10 kilometers per day.

00:07:14.190 --> 00:07:16.260
So you study that,
and you sit there.

00:07:16.260 --> 00:07:20.940
It is six months day, six months
dark, and six months day again.

00:07:20.940 --> 00:07:24.030
And this was 10 years ago.

00:07:24.030 --> 00:07:26.640
Big achievements-- we
changed crew members.

00:07:26.640 --> 00:07:28.370
We change scientists.

00:07:28.370 --> 00:07:31.920
We do rotation,
logistic rotation,

00:07:31.920 --> 00:07:35.220
to get the press people
on board and to tell

00:07:35.220 --> 00:07:36.450
the story of the Arctic--

00:07:36.450 --> 00:07:38.640
and then, again, fun unites.

00:07:38.640 --> 00:07:40.050
This was done 10 years ago.

00:07:40.050 --> 00:07:45.780
And then, back from this
upper North Pole area,

00:07:45.780 --> 00:07:47.790
we said OK, what's
going to be the fate

00:07:47.790 --> 00:07:51.629
of this ecosystem, the ocean
system, in a changing climate?

00:07:51.629 --> 00:07:52.670
What would be the future?

00:07:52.670 --> 00:07:54.000
What can we understand?

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:55.410
This is plankton.

00:07:55.410 --> 00:07:58.410
This is drifting
across the ocean

00:07:58.410 --> 00:08:02.570
everywhere-- billions and
billions of organisms.

00:08:02.570 --> 00:08:05.370
Colomban will talk to
you more about that.

00:08:05.370 --> 00:08:09.150
So we went to study this
ecosystem across the planet

00:08:09.150 --> 00:08:11.250
for four years on this track.

00:08:11.250 --> 00:08:12.200
And we collected.

00:08:12.200 --> 00:08:15.560
In every stop, we stopped and
we corrected fished plankton

00:08:15.560 --> 00:08:18.210
ecosystem, the world ecosystem.

00:08:18.210 --> 00:08:21.360
In the same way,
repeating, always

00:08:21.360 --> 00:08:23.880
the same kitchen on board,
the same infiltration--

00:08:23.880 --> 00:08:25.690
very boring.

00:08:25.690 --> 00:08:28.410
But you cannot imagine the
enthusiasm you can see on board

00:08:28.410 --> 00:08:32.700
of this voyage, because the
people believe that they were

00:08:32.700 --> 00:08:35.100
doing something that
was completely new.

00:08:35.100 --> 00:08:36.809
Like Colomban says
very often, it's

00:08:36.809 --> 00:08:42.659
like being in the
rainforest with the nets,

00:08:42.659 --> 00:08:46.770
catching birds and new things.

00:08:46.770 --> 00:08:49.680
So this was a crazy project,
including the Arctic ocean.

00:08:49.680 --> 00:08:52.140
And Colomban will talk to
you more about this science

00:08:52.140 --> 00:08:53.310
and this knowledge.

00:08:53.310 --> 00:08:55.290
We did study the
ecosystem completely--

00:08:55.290 --> 00:09:01.200
bacteria, viruses,
organisms, algaes.

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:02.130
We call it protist.

00:09:02.130 --> 00:09:04.940
He's a crazy protist
man, Colomban.

00:09:04.940 --> 00:09:07.644
Now, we are trying to
understand all this behavior.

00:09:07.644 --> 00:09:09.060
This is the fish
food that we talk

00:09:09.060 --> 00:09:11.490
about-- fish food, the
fish they eat that,

00:09:11.490 --> 00:09:15.130
and they rely on that.

00:09:15.130 --> 00:09:17.270
So far, we did a lot of data.

00:09:17.270 --> 00:09:18.450
It's a big ocean data.

00:09:18.450 --> 00:09:22.540
We got ocean life data,
molecular data, genomics,

00:09:22.540 --> 00:09:25.590
images, legal data
on every sample,

00:09:25.590 --> 00:09:29.420
because we were many
times in countries

00:09:29.420 --> 00:09:33.200
that owns these organisms.

00:09:33.200 --> 00:09:37.330
And we have other connectivity
with data centers.

00:09:37.330 --> 00:09:39.930
And this huge data is
one of the biggest,

00:09:39.930 --> 00:09:45.140
and the first time we describe
an ecosystem completely

00:09:45.140 --> 00:09:46.250
as a whole--

00:09:46.250 --> 00:09:48.250
the first time ever it is done.

00:09:48.250 --> 00:09:50.360
And Colomban will talk
to you about that.

00:09:50.360 --> 00:09:54.720
And these scientists we work
with across the world, 25

00:09:54.720 --> 00:09:57.470
laboratories from 10 countries,
they did publish in "Science,"

00:09:57.470 --> 00:09:59.770
did the cover of
"Science" two years ago.

00:09:59.770 --> 00:10:02.720
And this was the start of a
crazy adventure in science,

00:10:02.720 --> 00:10:05.630
and it's still ongoing
now even if we come back

00:10:05.630 --> 00:10:10.460
from this trip six years ago.

00:10:10.460 --> 00:10:14.270
Doing that, you fish
all these organisms.

00:10:14.270 --> 00:10:19.320
But also you fish a lot
of plastic, plastic bits

00:10:19.320 --> 00:10:22.020
that is degrading into
the ocean and that

00:10:22.020 --> 00:10:26.280
is catching all the
life of the ocean.

00:10:26.280 --> 00:10:28.980
It's also sticking
to it like a rock.

00:10:28.980 --> 00:10:32.930
It's nice to be at the sun
for algaes, enjoy this sun,

00:10:32.930 --> 00:10:33.930
make their life.

00:10:33.930 --> 00:10:37.170
And they are drifting
across the ocean like that.

00:10:37.170 --> 00:10:39.620
This is a simulation for
the Mediterranean Sea.

00:10:39.620 --> 00:10:41.890
You drop on the
model of the Med,

00:10:41.890 --> 00:10:47.027
you drop 10 particles in every
of these four main rivers.

00:10:47.027 --> 00:10:49.110
And you wait for a year
to see how are they going.

00:10:49.110 --> 00:10:51.430
This is a trimester.

00:10:51.430 --> 00:10:54.240
This is six months--

00:10:54.240 --> 00:10:57.620
10 particles every day a year.

00:10:57.620 --> 00:11:01.160
This is about to be 3/4.

00:11:01.160 --> 00:11:03.340
You can see that
particles on the road

00:11:03.340 --> 00:11:06.620
are going up to Alexandria at
the end of the year-- which

00:11:06.620 --> 00:11:10.700
is completely crazy how what
we do on land, what we do

00:11:10.700 --> 00:11:13.520
in our cities, in our
daily life, the impact

00:11:13.520 --> 00:11:16.880
we can have on the
ocean and its life.

00:11:16.880 --> 00:11:21.290
And you can see different
patterns, different streams

00:11:21.290 --> 00:11:24.080
across the Mediterranean Sea--

00:11:24.080 --> 00:11:25.590
just to show you the impact.

00:11:25.590 --> 00:11:28.799
So we did a crazy
seven months journey

00:11:28.799 --> 00:11:29.840
in the Mediterranean Sea.

00:11:29.840 --> 00:11:32.630
We collected these
plastic things

00:11:32.630 --> 00:11:36.200
over seven months,
300 locations.

00:11:36.200 --> 00:11:38.810
And we are now
still studying them.

00:11:42.360 --> 00:11:45.420
Coming back from
this expedition,

00:11:45.420 --> 00:11:50.670
one of the main ecosystems on
the planet besides plankton--

00:11:50.670 --> 00:11:52.957
in terms of biodiversity
of the ocean,

00:11:52.957 --> 00:11:54.540
that is storing a
lot of biodiversity,

00:11:54.540 --> 00:11:56.580
30% of the biodiversity--

00:11:56.580 --> 00:12:00.060
is linked to coral reefs.

00:12:00.060 --> 00:12:03.870
Very small places, but huge
diversity, huge ecosystem,

00:12:03.870 --> 00:12:06.820
huge biomass as well.

00:12:06.820 --> 00:12:10.410
So we decided to put
Tara for 2 and 1/2 years

00:12:10.410 --> 00:12:13.180
on an expedition to
study over the same,

00:12:13.180 --> 00:12:17.610
over the same samples, repeated
work over the 2 and 1/2 years

00:12:17.610 --> 00:12:21.690
to sample the reef,
its surrounding waters,

00:12:21.690 --> 00:12:24.510
the organisms, the animals.

00:12:24.510 --> 00:12:28.790
And I can show you here
the video-- please--

00:12:28.790 --> 00:12:31.920
a crazy video showing you
the super micro activity

00:12:31.920 --> 00:12:32.610
of coral reef.

00:12:32.610 --> 00:12:35.520
You're going to
see it's beautiful.

00:12:35.520 --> 00:12:38.280
And you will understand the
issues with garbage today.

00:12:38.280 --> 00:12:43.610
We will talk a lot about
bleaching reefs to get white.

00:12:43.610 --> 00:12:46.930
But first, look at the
beauty of these organisms.

00:12:46.930 --> 00:12:48.331
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:12:53.010 --> 00:12:56.490
So we have divers up top
diving in many, many places.

00:12:56.490 --> 00:13:00.080
So far, we did 20 states.

00:13:00.080 --> 00:13:01.750
These are states, small states.

00:13:08.820 --> 00:13:13.670
Now, if you look into details,
this is 10 centimeters.

00:13:13.670 --> 00:13:16.060
This is a millimeter.

00:13:16.060 --> 00:13:16.900
This is coral.

00:13:16.900 --> 00:13:17.990
This is an animal.

00:13:17.990 --> 00:13:21.740
It's like a jellyfish upside
down fixed on the rock,

00:13:21.740 --> 00:13:24.050
and it's feeding,
and it's sleeping.

00:13:24.050 --> 00:13:25.400
They are like us.

00:13:25.400 --> 00:13:26.520
They have bones inside.

00:13:31.640 --> 00:13:35.040
Corals are incredible.

00:13:35.040 --> 00:13:37.782
You can see these guys
getting out at night usually.

00:13:37.782 --> 00:13:39.240
They like that you
do not see them.

00:13:42.550 --> 00:13:44.145
And so they feed--
this is the mouth.

00:13:44.145 --> 00:13:45.130
This is an animal.

00:13:45.130 --> 00:13:46.570
They feed.

00:13:46.570 --> 00:13:48.310
The color you see
here is an algae

00:13:48.310 --> 00:13:50.770
they have in the body
that are giving them

00:13:50.770 --> 00:13:57.090
90% of the sugar they need to
live, 10% of what they eat.

00:13:57.090 --> 00:14:00.150
And when there is too much
stress, too much temperature,

00:14:00.150 --> 00:14:01.650
too high, they get white.

00:14:01.650 --> 00:14:04.140
The algae is going away.

00:14:04.140 --> 00:14:06.660
And if it lasts too
long, the animal

00:14:06.660 --> 00:14:09.240
maybe is starving and dies.

00:14:11.910 --> 00:14:17.762
And then it's completely covered
by sea grass in the ocean.

00:14:17.762 --> 00:14:18.720
This is climate change.

00:14:18.720 --> 00:14:21.140
This is what we talk about
now everywhere, every year.

00:14:25.220 --> 00:14:26.680
Even in very remote places--

00:14:26.680 --> 00:14:31.930
this is 4,000 kilometers
from any towns in the world.

00:14:31.930 --> 00:14:39.020
[INAUDIBLE] All white.

00:14:39.020 --> 00:14:40.470
So this is not a direct impact.

00:14:40.470 --> 00:14:43.530
This is really a global impact.

00:14:43.530 --> 00:14:46.530
And today, we have
very few understanding

00:14:46.530 --> 00:14:48.480
of what's going on,
how the Scar Reef

00:14:48.480 --> 00:14:56.350
is behaving, what other
mechanisms-- the process inside

00:14:56.350 --> 00:15:00.058
to resist climate change,
to resist pollution.

00:15:06.150 --> 00:15:09.900
And we were used to
main El Nino events

00:15:09.900 --> 00:15:12.650
of warming of the
Pacific every six,

00:15:12.650 --> 00:15:15.730
seven years over
the last 50 years.

00:15:15.730 --> 00:15:17.580
