00:19:10.870 --> 00:19:12.800
OK, so I'm Colomban.

00:19:12.800 --> 00:19:16.250
I am not a sailor, but I
am a Swiss oceanographer.

00:19:16.250 --> 00:19:20.730
And I was very lucky to meet,
actually, Romain and also

00:19:20.730 --> 00:19:23.410
this person that Romain
mentioned already,

00:19:23.410 --> 00:19:25.286
Eric Karsenti.

00:19:25.286 --> 00:19:27.750
I'm not sure if this
is working or not.

00:19:27.750 --> 00:19:28.400
Yeah, it works.

00:19:28.400 --> 00:19:32.150
So Eric is an amazing cell
biologist from the EMBL.

00:19:32.150 --> 00:19:34.130
He spent, like, 30
years of his life trying

00:19:34.130 --> 00:19:37.222
to understand how cell auto--

00:19:37.222 --> 00:19:38.180
you know, cell divides.

00:19:38.180 --> 00:19:40.160
And how all molecules
within the cell

00:19:40.160 --> 00:19:41.570
take a shape and auto-organize.

00:19:41.570 --> 00:19:43.520
So it's the science
of self-organization

00:19:43.520 --> 00:19:46.610
using statistics,
mechanics, you know,

00:19:46.610 --> 00:19:49.040
and so it's really that
the shaping of life

00:19:49.040 --> 00:19:50.550
with the element of life.

00:19:50.550 --> 00:19:53.060
And when I met Eric, he
showed me this movie,

00:19:53.060 --> 00:19:54.050
which is a zebrafish.

00:19:54.050 --> 00:19:57.860
So you can see here all the
cell of a little fish dividing.

00:19:57.860 --> 00:20:00.900
So it's a real fish
under a spin microscope.

00:20:00.900 --> 00:20:04.260
And you can see this baby fish
taking shape under your eyes--

00:20:04.260 --> 00:20:05.934
single-- all the cells.

00:20:05.934 --> 00:20:07.850
So it's just amazing,
and it was the beginning

00:20:07.850 --> 00:20:09.495
of spin microscopy.

00:20:09.495 --> 00:20:11.120
And so this is really
self-organization

00:20:11.120 --> 00:20:12.440
of an organism.

00:20:12.440 --> 00:20:15.890
And when Eric showed me this
in 2007, I was thinking, OK,

00:20:15.890 --> 00:20:17.020
I should follow this guy.

00:20:17.020 --> 00:20:20.690
And I should-- and Eric,
besides being an amazing--

00:20:20.690 --> 00:20:22.480
so he did all this in his lab.

00:20:22.480 --> 00:20:24.770
They developed the
best microscope.

00:20:24.770 --> 00:20:26.930
And Eric, he's a great sailor.

00:20:26.930 --> 00:20:30.569
He's an amazing sailor, but
he never looked in the ocean--

00:20:30.569 --> 00:20:31.610
of the life in the ocean.

00:20:31.610 --> 00:20:34.010
But he was brave
enough to think, OK,

00:20:34.010 --> 00:20:36.240
let's try to understand
the ocean that way.

00:20:36.240 --> 00:20:40.230
And that's always
what we had in mind.

00:20:40.230 --> 00:20:44.255
So basically, we are--

00:20:44.255 --> 00:20:47.300
today, we are really entering
this era of ecosystems.

00:20:47.300 --> 00:20:51.260
And we don't see any organisms
anymore as a single organism

00:20:51.260 --> 00:20:54.870
but as an ecosystem and
mainly human body, right?

00:20:54.870 --> 00:20:57.730
You know, there are millions
now of euros and dollars spent

00:20:57.730 --> 00:21:00.352
to understand how many
microbial genes-- because we

00:21:00.352 --> 00:21:02.810
are many more microbial genes
in our body than human genes.

00:21:02.810 --> 00:21:05.930
We have only 25,000 human genes.

00:21:05.930 --> 00:21:07.670
We have many more
bacterial cells

00:21:07.670 --> 00:21:09.510
than human cells in our body.

00:21:09.510 --> 00:21:13.210
So today, we really see
the human as an ecosystem.

00:21:13.210 --> 00:21:17.090
And so we start to want to
map all the cells of human.

00:21:17.090 --> 00:21:20.210
I don't know if you have heard
about this new project called

00:21:20.210 --> 00:21:22.820
Human Cell Atlas, which is
actually funded, essentially,

00:21:22.820 --> 00:21:26.600
by Zuckerberg, by the
Facebook Foundation.

00:21:26.600 --> 00:21:31.117
Now we have the technology
to sequence single cell of--

00:21:31.117 --> 00:21:33.200
the genome of single cells,
of the expressed genes

00:21:33.200 --> 00:21:34.160
of single cell.

00:21:34.160 --> 00:21:36.261
And the idea here is
to map all the cells,

00:21:36.261 --> 00:21:38.510
because we don't even know
how many different cells we

00:21:38.510 --> 00:21:40.400
have in the human body.

00:21:40.400 --> 00:21:42.404
But each-- all the cells
take different shape.

00:21:42.404 --> 00:21:44.570
Based on the same genome,
they take different shape.

00:21:44.570 --> 00:21:47.000
And they make ourselves, right?

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:51.470
So we really have this
ecosystemic vision of human.

00:21:51.470 --> 00:21:53.360
And in fact, what
we forget often--

00:21:53.360 --> 00:21:55.340
and this is very interesting.

00:21:55.340 --> 00:21:56.350
This is a human cell.

00:21:56.350 --> 00:21:57.225
This is a macrophage.

00:21:57.225 --> 00:21:58.850
You have this cell
in your blood now.

00:21:58.850 --> 00:22:01.760
You have thousands of
these cells in your body

00:22:01.760 --> 00:22:02.719
hunting for bacteria.

00:22:02.719 --> 00:22:03.885
You have here the leukocyte.

00:22:03.885 --> 00:22:05.480
It's another type of cell.

00:22:05.480 --> 00:22:07.850
And this cell has just
eaten-- so it's cleaning

00:22:07.850 --> 00:22:09.920
your body out of bacteria.

00:22:09.920 --> 00:22:12.050
So it's really your ecosystem.

00:22:12.050 --> 00:22:17.450
And what is fascinating--
sorry, I was too fast--

00:22:17.450 --> 00:22:19.790
is that, in fact, if
you go to the ocean,

00:22:19.790 --> 00:22:24.900
you can see this kind of
cell that's an amoeba,

00:22:24.900 --> 00:22:27.620
for instance, you know,
hunting for microalgae

00:22:27.620 --> 00:22:28.650
here-- microalgae.

00:22:28.650 --> 00:22:29.970
And the resemblance is amazing.

00:22:29.970 --> 00:22:31.553
And in fact, you
know, the composition

00:22:31.553 --> 00:22:33.570
in salt between your
blood and the ocean

00:22:33.570 --> 00:22:35.210
is strictly almost the same.

00:22:35.210 --> 00:22:37.020
The content of salt
is almost the same.

00:22:37.020 --> 00:22:39.030
The proportion is
different, but we are really

00:22:39.030 --> 00:22:41.310
a walking piece of ocean.

00:22:41.310 --> 00:22:42.180
And so I think--

00:22:42.180 --> 00:22:45.090
so the origin of life,
you know, is in the ocean.

00:22:45.090 --> 00:22:47.490
All these organisms have
invented all the genes we have

00:22:47.490 --> 00:22:49.652
and all the shape we
have in our cells.

00:22:49.652 --> 00:22:51.110
And so we really
need to understand

00:22:51.110 --> 00:22:53.820
these systems, which is much
more complex than human,

00:22:53.820 --> 00:22:54.910
of course.

00:22:54.910 --> 00:22:58.570
So what we decided
in 2008 was really

00:22:58.570 --> 00:23:03.380
to jump into the big bath and
to go to this, like Romain said,

00:23:03.380 --> 00:23:07.200
to this global ocean, which,
in every liter of seawater,

00:23:07.200 --> 00:23:09.720
you have between 10 and 100
billion organisms, including

00:23:09.720 --> 00:23:11.910
viruses, in every liter.

00:23:11.910 --> 00:23:13.600
And the ocean
generates all this.

00:23:13.600 --> 00:23:15.060
It's actually not a blue planet.

00:23:15.060 --> 00:23:16.422
It's a blue-green planet.

00:23:16.422 --> 00:23:17.880
You have all this
green here, which

00:23:17.880 --> 00:23:21.050
is photosynthetic
cells, like the tree,

00:23:21.050 --> 00:23:25.290
but single-cell organisms,
which produce half of the oxygen

00:23:25.290 --> 00:23:27.930
that we breathe on the planet.

00:23:27.930 --> 00:23:30.940
The ocean is also extremely
reactive to global change.

00:23:30.940 --> 00:23:33.180
So it will feedback
on climate very fast.

00:23:33.180 --> 00:23:35.700
So we really need to
understand how this feedback--

00:23:35.700 --> 00:23:37.430
the resilience of
the system, and how

00:23:37.430 --> 00:23:41.100
it will give us an answer to
what we pose to planet Earth.

00:23:43.740 --> 00:23:48.390
So we decided basically to, in
this era of ecosystems biology,

00:23:48.390 --> 00:23:49.110
to--

00:23:49.110 --> 00:23:52.870
so Eric spent 30 years on
this, billions of euros.

00:23:52.870 --> 00:23:54.620
Now there are many,
many projects on this.

00:23:54.620 --> 00:23:57.520
It's also billions of dollars.

00:23:57.520 --> 00:24:01.110
So we decided to go directly to
this one, to the full system--

00:24:01.110 --> 00:24:03.460
planet Earth, the
biggest system.

00:24:03.460 --> 00:24:06.330
And the advantage of this system
over classical system that we

00:24:06.330 --> 00:24:09.870
know, ecosystem that we
know better-- maybe as kids,

00:24:09.870 --> 00:24:11.790
you know, because we
see these systems--

00:24:11.790 --> 00:24:14.350
is that in these ecosystems,
organisms are very big.

00:24:14.350 --> 00:24:16.540
So it's very difficult
to sample these systems.

00:24:16.540 --> 00:24:19.590
A forest, it's impossible
to sample trees.

00:24:19.590 --> 00:24:23.310
And also the dynamic of these
ecosystems is very slow.

00:24:23.310 --> 00:24:24.900
The climax of-- the
life of a forest

00:24:24.900 --> 00:24:27.960
is bigger than a human
life, while in the plankton,

00:24:27.960 --> 00:24:29.400
you have a bit of everything.

00:24:29.400 --> 00:24:31.870
You have, you will see,
you have a bit of all life,

00:24:31.870 --> 00:24:32.620
but it's changing.

00:24:32.620 --> 00:24:33.390
It's reorganizing.

00:24:33.390 --> 00:24:35.540
Like the fish, you know--

00:24:35.540 --> 00:24:37.740
during the highlight I
showed the baby fish--

00:24:37.740 --> 00:24:39.210
it's all the time reorganizing.

00:24:39.210 --> 00:24:41.950
So we think we can understand
fundamental principle

00:24:41.950 --> 00:24:45.609
of ecosystemics.

00:24:45.609 --> 00:24:47.150
So the beauty of
plankton, as I said,

00:24:47.150 --> 00:24:50.860
is that you don't have the
10th orders of magnitude

00:24:50.860 --> 00:24:52.900
across which life develop.

00:24:52.900 --> 00:24:55.360
It stops, basically,
at a few centimeters.

00:24:55.360 --> 00:24:57.550
And so we developed a
protocol to sample plankton

00:24:57.550 --> 00:25:01.900
from viruses to bacteria,
to protists, to animals.

00:25:01.900 --> 00:25:04.030
And there is no plants,
because photosynthesis

00:25:04.030 --> 00:25:06.220
is done by these protists.

00:25:06.220 --> 00:25:07.900
We put on the boat--

00:25:07.900 --> 00:25:10.960
so it was crazy,
because it was in 2008.

00:25:10.960 --> 00:25:14.520
We had very little
time to equip the boat.

00:25:14.520 --> 00:25:16.470
What was fantastic
that we started

00:25:16.470 --> 00:25:19.210
was the flexibility, the
reactivity, which you can never

00:25:19.210 --> 00:25:22.990
do in classical-- in academia.

00:25:22.990 --> 00:25:25.129
So we equipped the lab.

00:25:25.129 --> 00:25:26.920
And we were very lucky,
because it was just

00:25:26.920 --> 00:25:29.780
the beginning of the high
throughput sequencing

00:25:29.780 --> 00:25:31.940
with the Illumina method.

00:25:31.940 --> 00:25:34.390
So it was just the time
where the price of sequencing

00:25:34.390 --> 00:25:36.820
was dropping terribly.

00:25:36.820 --> 00:25:39.900
And so we had different
nets and pumps

00:25:39.900 --> 00:25:41.620
to sample this-- for plankton.

00:25:41.620 --> 00:25:44.230
We also had a very
nice rosette, which

00:25:44.230 --> 00:25:47.560
is an instrument to measure all
kinds of underwater parameters.

00:25:47.560 --> 00:25:50.440
So I will tell you about
the data we collected.

00:25:50.440 --> 00:25:54.800
We collected data in omics,
so basically, DNA and RNA

00:25:54.800 --> 00:25:56.790
expressed genes.

00:25:56.790 --> 00:25:59.080
Just for the people
who like data,

00:25:59.080 --> 00:26:03.890
we collected about 900
billion Illumina DNA reads.

00:26:03.890 --> 00:26:07.520
That's more than 90
terabases raw DNA data

00:26:07.520 --> 00:26:09.370
from seven
organismal-size fractions,

00:26:09.370 --> 00:26:13.420
from viruses to animals, and
from about more than 4,000

00:26:13.420 --> 00:26:14.760
plankton communities.

00:26:18.360 --> 00:26:21.520
Yeah, this is just again
the number of data,

00:26:21.520 --> 00:26:24.310
the number of computing
time we have used for now,

00:26:24.310 --> 00:26:29.830
and the number of analyses
that we have done.

00:26:29.830 --> 00:26:32.010
And as you can see, it's--

00:26:32.010 --> 00:26:35.700
by far, it's two-time-- twice--

00:26:35.700 --> 00:26:39.600
100 times higher than the
next project in ocean systems

00:26:39.600 --> 00:26:40.264
ecology.

00:26:40.264 --> 00:26:41.430
So it's really the biggest--

00:26:41.430 --> 00:26:45.670
by far the biggest ecosystemic
project in the ocean.

00:26:45.670 --> 00:26:47.540
What is very hard in
ecology is to collect

00:26:47.540 --> 00:26:49.710
homogeneous data,
standardized data

00:26:49.710 --> 00:26:52.620
across sufficient
spatiotemporal scale.

00:26:52.620 --> 00:26:54.980
So this is for the DNA data.

00:26:54.980 --> 00:26:56.510
And then we-- this
is very original.

00:26:56.510 --> 00:26:59.580
We used a lot of instruments.

00:26:59.580 --> 00:27:01.411
Flow cytometry-- this
one, we developed.

00:27:01.411 --> 00:27:03.410
And I will tell you a few
words about this one--

00:27:03.410 --> 00:27:05.930
FlowCAM, ZooScan, and UVP--

00:27:05.930 --> 00:27:07.470
to image, as well, the plankton.

00:27:07.470 --> 00:27:09.345
So we took a lot of
images of those organisms

00:27:09.345 --> 00:27:12.540
at the same site at
a different depth.

00:27:12.540 --> 00:27:14.832
And so this was this--
we haven't almost

00:27:14.832 --> 00:27:15.540
touched the data.

00:27:15.540 --> 00:27:17.810
You know, it's very--

00:27:17.810 --> 00:27:18.980
and so we got--

00:27:18.980 --> 00:27:22.320
for now, we have six
million images of plankton.

00:27:22.320 --> 00:27:24.750
A lot of them are already
validated by experts.

00:27:24.750 --> 00:27:26.700
And we have-- yeah,
which represent more

00:27:26.700 --> 00:27:28.710
than 330 terabytes of data.

00:27:31.240 --> 00:27:36.080
We also have done a
website, which I think--

00:27:36.080 --> 00:27:40.800
an instrument on the web,
an online image platform

00:27:40.800 --> 00:27:42.990
to basically share this
image project-by-project

00:27:42.990 --> 00:27:44.310
with experts.

00:27:44.310 --> 00:27:47.040
Because we need a
semi-automated machine learning

00:27:47.040 --> 00:27:51.300
processes to learn the machine
to recognize the images.

00:27:51.300 --> 00:27:53.100
And so there is
no, you know-- also

00:27:53.100 --> 00:27:54.930
there is a gene bank for genes.

00:27:54.930 --> 00:27:57.300
There is international
banks for genes.

00:27:57.300 --> 00:28:00.840
There is nothing equivalent for
images in ecology in science.

00:28:00.840 --> 00:28:04.230
So it's really something
that we need to think about.

00:28:04.230 --> 00:28:06.480
OK, time-- now let's get
into the data itself.

00:28:06.480 --> 00:28:10.000
So it will be a bit harder.

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:12.720
So we publish this wonderful
special issue in "Science."

00:28:12.720 --> 00:28:14.980
And of course, we have now--

00:28:14.980 --> 00:28:19.350
I think we have published
150 papers since 2009.

00:28:19.350 --> 00:28:22.060
It's hard to speak
about it in 10 minutes.

00:28:22.060 --> 00:28:24.640
But what we can
say from this data,

00:28:24.640 --> 00:28:28.470
I think, here the three
papers concerned viruses,

00:28:28.470 --> 00:28:31.400
the bacteria, and eukaryotes.

00:28:31.400 --> 00:28:34.590
Eukaryotes are us--
cells with a nucleus.

00:28:34.590 --> 00:28:35.470
And what is amazing--

00:28:35.470 --> 00:28:37.261
you don't need to look
at the detail, but--

00:28:37.261 --> 00:28:41.370
is that we saturate
many of these diversity.

00:28:41.370 --> 00:28:43.530
Meaning that the
more we sequence,

00:28:43.530 --> 00:28:45.300
the less we find new things.

00:28:45.300 --> 00:28:49.079
And basically, we sampled
the ocean largely enough,

00:28:49.079 --> 00:28:51.120
the surface of the ocean--
and this was just from

00:28:51.120 --> 00:28:52.500
the surface--

00:28:52.500 --> 00:28:55.540
to basically not see
anymore anything new.

00:28:55.540 --> 00:28:57.480
So we push the
diversity very far away.

00:28:57.480 --> 00:29:00.810
We sequenced 40 million
protein-coding genes

00:29:00.810 --> 00:29:02.440
for bacteria.

00:29:02.440 --> 00:29:04.417
But we see most of them,
which is fantastic.

00:29:04.417 --> 00:29:06.000
So we see the limit
of this diversity.

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:09.690
So we can start to think
in terms of ecosystemics.

00:29:09.690 --> 00:29:12.060
There is just one compartment
that we didn't saturate,

00:29:12.060 --> 00:29:14.880
and this is the eukaryotes,
eukaryotic cells,

00:29:14.880 --> 00:29:16.620
like ourselves.

00:29:16.620 --> 00:29:19.200
We sequence more and more,
and there is many more new.

00:29:19.200 --> 00:29:23.210
So we are now reaching 150
million eukaryotic genes

00:29:23.210 --> 00:29:24.750
in this plankton.

00:29:24.750 --> 00:29:26.600
And it's endless.

00:29:26.600 --> 00:29:28.380
We are far from saturation.

00:29:28.380 --> 00:29:31.260
In fact, most of these
genes are unknown.

00:29:31.260 --> 00:29:35.100
They don't look anything
that we have in the database.

00:29:35.100 --> 00:29:38.490
And the other one, we can't just
attach them to known things,

00:29:38.490 --> 00:29:40.830
but it's very unsure yet.

00:29:40.830 --> 00:29:42.112
So this is really amazing.

00:29:42.112 --> 00:29:43.320
And in fact, I think we are--

00:29:45.942 --> 00:29:47.400
just to show you
an example of what

00:29:47.400 --> 00:29:51.570
we can see now with image data
with using these instruments.

00:29:51.570 --> 00:29:54.105
We just take a picture
of the marine snow.

00:29:54.105 --> 00:29:56.010
The marine snow is
all these organisms

00:29:56.010 --> 00:29:58.040
that fall down to the
bottom of the ocean,

00:29:58.040 --> 00:30:00.360
and which is actually the
mechanism that maintains also

00:30:00.360 --> 00:30:03.704
the atmosphere we breathe.

00:30:03.704 --> 00:30:05.120
With this instrument,
we learned--

00:30:05.120 --> 00:30:06.210
we teach the instrument--

00:30:06.210 --> 00:30:07.160
I mean, the data--

00:30:07.160 --> 00:30:09.630
to recognize this
kind of shape, which

00:30:09.630 --> 00:30:11.700
correspond to giant protists.

00:30:11.700 --> 00:30:14.760
And we realized that these
giant protists in fact

00:30:14.760 --> 00:30:18.990
have a bigger biomass than
all animals in the plankton,

00:30:18.990 --> 00:30:22.620
in the subtropical and
tropical regime here.

00:30:25.401 --> 00:30:26.400
And they look like that.

00:30:26.400 --> 00:30:29.394
No one knows these
Rhizaria, these [INAUDIBLE]..

00:30:29.394 --> 00:30:30.810
I think there was,
like, something

00:30:30.810 --> 00:30:32.310
like 90 species described.

00:30:32.310 --> 00:30:35.830
These guys are
running the world.

00:30:35.830 --> 00:30:37.950
If you dive in there in
the middle of the ocean,

00:30:37.950 --> 00:30:40.150
you will see tons of these
little guys floating.

00:30:40.150 --> 00:30:42.630
They are beautiful creatures
in symbiosis with algae-like--

00:30:42.630 --> 00:30:44.220
or they are a bit
like piece of corals

00:30:44.220 --> 00:30:47.370
floating around the world.

00:30:47.370 --> 00:30:51.570
I think we are almost coming
to a new theory of life

00:30:51.570 --> 00:30:53.340
of biological diversity.

00:30:53.340 --> 00:30:55.350
For a long time we
thought that life was--

00:30:55.350 --> 00:30:59.070
for three centuries-- that
life was in animals and plants,

00:30:59.070 --> 00:31:01.830
and the diversity was
decreasing toward microbes.

00:31:01.830 --> 00:31:05.359
Then over the last few years,
over the last three decades,

00:31:05.359 --> 00:31:06.900
because they started--
people started

00:31:06.900 --> 00:31:10.050
to sequence the
small animals, we

00:31:10.050 --> 00:31:13.800
saw that the diversity was
in the viruses and bacteria.

00:31:13.800 --> 00:31:17.690
And now that we have a real
ecosystemic view of our system,

00:31:17.690 --> 00:31:19.850
we see that there is
a peak of diversity

00:31:19.850 --> 00:31:22.270
of genes of organisms
in the middle,

00:31:22.270 --> 00:31:24.827
like, between a few
microns and 15 microns.

00:31:24.827 --> 00:31:26.660
That's where, really,
life has complexified.

00:31:26.660 --> 00:31:29.960
And no one has studied this
piece of life, you know?

00:31:29.960 --> 00:31:31.710
So we speak about diversity.

00:31:31.710 --> 00:31:33.740
Now we know that
diversity is there.

00:31:33.740 --> 00:31:37.730
And we actually have sequenced--
we went to the Amazon Forest.

00:31:37.730 --> 00:31:38.810
And it's the same.

00:31:38.810 --> 00:31:40.850
You find this peak
of life, which

00:31:40.850 --> 00:31:44.270
I call life's middle class,
lower-middle class, in fact.

00:31:44.270 --> 00:31:46.730
So these organisms
look like that.

00:31:46.730 --> 00:31:48.490
They are my obsession a bit--

00:31:48.490 --> 00:31:49.940
protists.

00:31:49.940 --> 00:31:52.760
So at least I want you
to remember this name.

00:31:52.760 --> 00:31:56.990
And so protists are beautiful
creatures, single-celled.

00:31:56.990 --> 00:31:59.870
So they have very
complex genomes.

00:31:59.870 --> 00:32:01.370
They can build
beautiful skeletons.

00:32:01.370 --> 00:32:04.130
Here you have some
coccolithophores.

00:32:04.130 --> 00:32:06.627
This is always one cell.

00:32:06.627 --> 00:32:07.710
This is one cell building.

00:32:07.710 --> 00:32:09.140
So the cell is living inside.

00:32:09.140 --> 00:32:10.850
And it's building up
these little plates

00:32:10.850 --> 00:32:13.230
and assembling them
outside the cell.

00:32:13.230 --> 00:32:16.160
You can see how these
cells are powerful.

00:32:16.160 --> 00:32:17.600
This is actually
one of the cells

00:32:17.600 --> 00:32:19.640
building the plate inside the--

00:32:19.640 --> 00:32:22.660
inside some vesicle and
extruding the plates.

00:32:22.660 --> 00:32:25.310
This cell is the most
calcifying organism on Earth.

00:32:25.310 --> 00:32:26.240
You can see it--

00:32:26.240 --> 00:32:28.980
the cell [INAUDIBLE] the
Black Sea here, in summer,

00:32:28.980 --> 00:32:31.670
at some time of the year.

00:32:31.670 --> 00:32:33.650
And these cells-- so
for instance, this cell

00:32:33.650 --> 00:32:35.780
is at the same time a
plant and an animal.

00:32:35.780 --> 00:32:36.870
It can eat.

00:32:36.870 --> 00:32:38.410
It can photosynthesize.

00:32:38.410 --> 00:32:41.900
It can build this marvelous
nanotechnology pieces

00:32:41.900 --> 00:32:43.850
and transform the Earth
system, as you can

00:32:43.850 --> 00:32:46.990
see from the geological record.

00:32:46.990 --> 00:32:53.780
The shore of Dover here is of
100% coccolithophore, almost.

00:32:53.780 --> 00:32:56.300
So they have an impact, a
major impact, probably stronger

00:32:56.300 --> 00:32:59.640
than the one we have,
actually, today.

00:32:59.640 --> 00:33:02.730
So with protist,
a new world that

00:33:02.730 --> 00:33:05.870
is now coming into the
game of global ecology--

00:33:05.870 --> 00:33:08.602
and now what we want to try
also to do a lot is to assemble

00:33:08.602 --> 00:33:09.560
all these complex data.

00:33:09.560 --> 00:33:11.060
So we have different
layers of data.

00:33:11.060 --> 00:33:13.640
We have ecological data.

00:33:13.640 --> 00:33:16.800
We have genomes, genes,
organisms, and satellite data

00:33:16.800 --> 00:33:17.300
as well.

00:33:17.300 --> 00:33:20.180
So we have different
heterogeneous complex data

00:33:20.180 --> 00:33:25.649
that we try to put together
with graph-based methods.

00:33:25.649 --> 00:33:26.690
And so we did this paper.

00:33:26.690 --> 00:33:29.700
We built up the first
global plankton interactome.

00:33:29.700 --> 00:33:32.870
And what we saw is that biotic
interactions are more important

00:33:32.870 --> 00:33:36.770
abiotic interactions, and
that there are much more

00:33:36.770 --> 00:33:39.500
taxon-taxon interaction
in this network

00:33:39.500 --> 00:33:42.320
rather than
taxon-environmental parameters.

00:33:42.320 --> 00:33:45.950
And that corporation,
positive relation,

00:33:45.950 --> 00:33:48.770
are much more important
than exclusive relation,

00:33:48.770 --> 00:33:51.620
which is kind of a nice
lesson, I think, of life.

00:33:51.620 --> 00:33:54.180
And now you can analyze this.

00:33:54.180 --> 00:33:56.660
It's going to take years
to understand really

00:33:56.660 --> 00:33:59.700
what functions are
driving these networks,

00:33:59.700 --> 00:34:01.970
these big ecological networks.

00:34:01.970 --> 00:34:04.665
What we have found for instance
is that, in fact, parasites

00:34:04.665 --> 00:34:07.720
are incredibly abundant
but nice parasites.

00:34:07.720 --> 00:34:09.860
These parasites try
not to kill their host,

00:34:09.860 --> 00:34:11.350
because they need their host.

00:34:11.350 --> 00:34:14.600
So parasitism seems to be a
big driver of the stability

00:34:14.600 --> 00:34:15.600
of the network.

00:34:15.600 --> 00:34:17.690
In fact, we know as
humans that we don't

00:34:17.690 --> 00:34:19.150
have enough parasites probably.

00:34:19.150 --> 00:34:22.139
Now there is a medicine that
think that we should get back

00:34:22.139 --> 00:34:26.460
our parasites to be healthier.

00:34:26.460 --> 00:34:33.739
We also started to
basically use this network,

00:34:33.739 --> 00:34:35.870
because this network
is really the ecology

00:34:35.870 --> 00:34:37.520
of a complex system-- plankton.

00:34:37.520 --> 00:34:40.520
Now we try also to mix it
to other complex systems,

00:34:40.520 --> 00:34:45.350
like biogeochemical cycles,
like the carbon pump, which

00:34:45.350 --> 00:34:48.949
is a very important fundamental
mechanism of the biosphere

00:34:48.949 --> 00:34:51.400
or climate processes.

00:34:51.400 --> 00:34:53.540
So in this paper,
we try to extract

00:34:53.540 --> 00:34:56.420
the most important component
of the network, which are not

00:34:56.420 --> 00:34:57.790
often the most abundant.

00:34:57.790 --> 00:35:00.170
Often they are the
most connected.

00:35:00.170 --> 00:35:01.940
Two fundamental
processes of the carbon

00:35:01.940 --> 00:35:05.030
flux that we measured with this
instrument I showed you before,

00:35:05.030 --> 00:35:08.320
the UVP, Underwater
Video Profiler.

00:35:08.320 --> 00:35:11.030
And we found that specific
plankton communities correlate

00:35:11.030 --> 00:35:13.804
with carbon export, in
particular, with radiolarians,

00:35:13.804 --> 00:35:15.220
dinoflagellates,
and synechococcus

00:35:15.220 --> 00:35:17.880
is very important--
different species.

00:35:17.880 --> 00:35:20.040
And we can predict
actually the carbon export

00:35:20.040 --> 00:35:25.620
with part of these networks
at a very high accuracy.

00:35:25.620 --> 00:35:28.026
So now where are we?

00:35:28.026 --> 00:35:32.220
I think we need to
have a job, I think.

00:35:32.220 --> 00:35:36.150
I think we had about--
because we sample, you know,

00:35:36.150 --> 00:35:42.080
220 sites, three depths, and
so we have about, I think,

00:35:42.080 --> 00:35:46.079
600 ecosystem in this
global body of the ocean.

00:35:46.079 --> 00:35:47.370
But the ocean is super complex.

00:35:47.370 --> 00:35:49.440
It's super dynamic.

00:35:49.440 --> 00:35:51.410
You have a lot of connection.

00:35:51.410 --> 00:35:53.100
You have this big
gyre, who have, like,

00:35:53.100 --> 00:35:54.420
300 kilometers large.

00:35:54.420 --> 00:35:57.555
And it take them three
years to cross the Atlantic.

00:35:57.555 --> 00:36:01.194
And so we need, of
course, more expedition.

00:36:01.194 --> 00:36:02.610
And we need to
expand the approach

00:36:02.610 --> 00:36:08.899
we have on very clever
temporal and spatial scales.

00:36:08.899 --> 00:36:11.190
So Romain told you about--
so now we have a new project

00:36:11.190 --> 00:36:15.640
today, which is called
TO-SEE, Tara Oceans Systems

00:36:15.640 --> 00:36:17.970
Ecology and Evolution,
where we try to-- this

00:36:17.970 --> 00:36:20.070
is the data I just showed you.

00:36:20.070 --> 00:36:23.490
This is what I call now the
symbiome, made of bacteria,

00:36:23.490 --> 00:36:27.030
of protists, and animals,
metabolists, shapes,

00:36:27.030 --> 00:36:28.065
and behavior.

00:36:31.626 --> 00:36:33.000
We have a new
project, basically,

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:36.250
is to expand the
approach we have done

00:36:36.250 --> 00:36:39.420
over different spatiotemporal
scales that will allow

00:36:39.420 --> 00:36:42.910
us to understand the system.

00:36:42.910 --> 00:36:49.270
One very important aspect is
there is an incredibly good

00:36:49.270 --> 00:36:51.700
platform to develop
new protocols

00:36:51.700 --> 00:36:55.270
and to do very, very
actually hardcore science.

00:36:55.270 --> 00:36:58.210
But there is also between
10 and 15,000 sailing boats

00:36:58.210 --> 00:37:01.570
at any time in the ocean
crossing the ocean.

00:37:01.570 --> 00:37:05.710
And we started to transfer part
of the best protocol we have

00:37:05.710 --> 00:37:09.490
done to these sailors, which
we call now the Plankton odes

00:37:09.490 --> 00:37:11.890
in this Plankton Planet project.

00:37:11.890 --> 00:37:14.110
We have basically
extracted a little protocol

00:37:14.110 --> 00:37:19.120
to collect plankton very
easily, and a little kit that

00:37:19.120 --> 00:37:22.120
allows them to get
a little plankton,

00:37:22.120 --> 00:37:24.310
and send us through the--

00:37:24.310 --> 00:37:26.350
actually, they dry the plankton.

00:37:26.350 --> 00:37:29.650
And they send us just
a galette of plankton

00:37:29.650 --> 00:37:30.940
to the lab directly.

00:37:30.940 --> 00:37:33.310
And we could show--

00:37:33.310 --> 00:37:35.770
it was just a test
phase as a case study,

00:37:35.770 --> 00:37:38.560
but it was actually quite--
it was super-easy to find

00:37:38.560 --> 00:37:39.550
enough sailors.

00:37:39.550 --> 00:37:42.440
I mean, we had too many people
that wanted to participate.

00:37:42.440 --> 00:37:46.060
We had 25 crews who sailed
the planet in one year.

00:37:46.060 --> 00:37:50.130
And we could collect data
from all these dots here,

00:37:50.130 --> 00:37:51.340
these regimes.

00:37:51.340 --> 00:37:55.510
Here is the number of samples,
different boats collecting

00:37:55.510 --> 00:37:57.109
plankton.

00:37:57.109 --> 00:37:58.150
And we got all this data.

00:37:58.150 --> 00:38:01.330
And we sequenced it for
barcoding-- for DNA barcode.

00:38:01.330 --> 00:38:04.570
And here you can see, in red,
the number of new plankton

00:38:04.570 --> 00:38:07.420
genus that we never found in
our-- in this big data set

00:38:07.420 --> 00:38:10.710
I showed you, showing
that, in fact, we

00:38:10.710 --> 00:38:13.510
are reaching saturation, but
there is a lot to discover.

00:38:13.510 --> 00:38:17.080
And if we want to reach
a very fine granularity,

00:38:17.080 --> 00:38:19.090
we need these boat to help.

00:38:19.090 --> 00:38:20.890
Because there is
no automated way

00:38:20.890 --> 00:38:23.950
yet of sampling the
complexity of the ocean.

00:38:23.950 --> 00:38:26.950
The last point I wanted
to say is that we

00:38:26.950 --> 00:38:28.180
need to develop imaging.

00:38:28.180 --> 00:38:31.760
And we have developed
a fantastic approach

00:38:31.760 --> 00:38:34.550
to automatically image,
thanks to Eric Karsenti,

00:38:34.550 --> 00:38:37.000
and to come back to the
beginning of my talk.

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:38.740
We developed these new methods--

00:38:38.740 --> 00:38:41.740
this method that was
used in human biology--

00:38:41.740 --> 00:38:47.230
to do automatic, 3D,
high resolution imaging,

00:38:47.230 --> 00:38:50.347
confocal, of all the
cells that I showed you.

00:38:50.347 --> 00:38:52.680
And it's beautiful, because
